Norman origin): from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Hervei</i>, also found as <i>Herveu</i>, <i>Hervé</i>, and <i>Hervi</i>. The name <i>Herveu</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was borne by a number of Bretons at the Norman Conquest and, as such, represents a French form of the Old Breton name <i>Hoiearnviu</i> or <i>Hærviu</i> (see   Herve  ). Among Normans <i>Herve(i)</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was also a French form of ancient Germanic <i>Hariwic</i>, <i>Herewic</i> (from <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’), with intervocalic /w/ becoming /v/ in Old French. The Breton and ancient Germanic names were commonly Latinized as <i>Herve(i)us</i> and <i>Hervic(i)us</i> respectively but, since their most common vernacular forms in Old French were indistinguishable, the Latin forms were also sometimes interchangeable, especially <i>Herveus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAirmheadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Airmheadhach</i>’, a personal name probably meaning ‘esteemed’. It seems to be a derivative of <i>Airmheadh</i>, the name borne by a mythological physician.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarchaidh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earchadh</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Arvey","meanings":["English: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Harvie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Herve","meanings":["Breton (<b>Hervé</b>): from the Old Breton personal name <i>Hoiearnviu</i>, composed of the elements <i>hoiarn</i> ‘iron’ and <i>viu</i> ‘blazing’, or <i>Hærviu</i>, with the first element meaning ‘battle’ or ‘fort’.","French (<b>Hervé</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hariwig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ and <i>wig</i> ‘battle’. Compare   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Hervey","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Havey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Harvey  , although some instances in the historical records may be spelling errors."]},{"name":"Harvison","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): patronymic from the personal name   Harvey   + ‘son’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":71,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":100,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Harvey was born in 1500, in England. He married Sarah in 1520, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1503–Female":"1503–Surnud","1535–1560":"1535–1560","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","England":"England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1500–":"1500–Kuollut","1503–Female":"1503–Kuollut","1535–1560":"1535–1560","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","England":"England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1500–":"1500–Décédé","1503–Female":"1503–Décédée","1535–1560":"1535–1560","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre"